    <section class="guide-body">

      <p>
        The best preparation for selling a business is understanding exactly how buyers think.
        Buyers — and the SBA lenders who finance most Main Street acquisitions — evaluate businesses
        through a specific lens: earnings quality, transferability risk, and downside scenarios.
        This guide explains what buyers look for at each stage of the acquisition process and what
        you can do to present your business as the most attractive version of itself.
      </p>

      <h2>1. Verifiable, Consistent Earnings</h2>
      <p>
        The first question every buyer answers is: can I verify what this business actually makes?
        Reported SDE means nothing if the documentation to support it is incomplete. Buyers and their
        lenders will request:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>3 years of business tax returns (the primary source of truth)</li>
        <li>3 years of monthly P&amp;L statements (ideally from accounting software, not spreadsheets)</li>
        <li>Bank statements for the past 12–24 months to verify revenue deposits match reported figures</li>
        <li>Documentation of every add-back to SDE — payroll records, invoices, credit card statements</li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        The most common diligence failure: the seller's stated SDE includes add-backs that the financials
        don't support. A buyer who cannot independently verify the SDE will either renegotiate the price
        or walk. Use the <a href="/">valuation calculator</a> based on your documented SDE, not your
        total including undocumented add-backs.
      </p>

      <h2>2. Transferability: Will It Still Work Without You?</h2>
      <p>
        Buyers are buying the future earnings of the business — not its historical earnings under the
        current owner. The central transferability question: can a new owner, who is not you, generate
        the same earnings?
      </p>
      <p>
        Buyers evaluate transferability through:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>Staff stability and capability:</strong> Are there trained employees who can continue
          their roles under new ownership? Is any key role currently only filled by the owner?
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Customer relationships:</strong> Are customers loyal to the business or to you personally?
          Businesses where customers follow the owner have significantly lower transferability value.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Documented systems:</strong> Operations, hiring, vendor relationships, and customer
          onboarding should be documented in SOPs — not in the owner's head. A buyer who asks "how does
          X work?" and receives "I handle that" has identified a transferability risk.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Supplier and vendor relationships:</strong> Contracts and relationships in the owner's
          personal name, rather than the business entity, are a risk. Buyers need assurance these will
          transfer.
        </li>
      </ul>

      <h2>3. Revenue Quality: Recurring vs. Transactional</h2>
      <p>
        Not all revenue is equally valuable to a buyer. Recurring revenue — service contracts,
        subscriptions, maintenance agreements, memberships — generates predictable forward cash flow
        that a new owner can count on. Transactional revenue requires continuous marketing and sales
        effort to maintain.
      </p>
      <p>
        A home services business with 60% of revenue from annual maintenance contracts and 40%
        from new customer project work is worth more than an identical business with 100% project
        revenue — even if the SDE is the same. The contract revenue will continue post-acquisition;
        the project revenue requires the new owner to replicate the selling capability.
      </p>
      <p>
        When presenting your business, quantify your recurring revenue as a percentage of total revenue.
        This is one of the clearest signals of earnings quality you can give a buyer.
      </p>

      <h2>4. Customer Concentration</h2>
      <p>
        SBA lenders specifically flag customer concentration as a deal risk. If any single customer
        represents 20%+ of revenue, expect questions. If one customer represents 40%+ of revenue,
        expect either a price reduction, a holdback, or an earnout structure to hedge the post-close risk.
      </p>
      <p>
        Buyers look at your customer list during diligence. They will calculate your top-10 customer
        concentration and ask about the nature of each relationship. Long-standing contractual relationships
        with large institutional customers (municipalities, school districts, large commercial accounts)
        are less concerning than revenue concentrated in a few personal relationships that exist because
        of the seller's individual network.
      </p>

      <h2>5. The Lease and Physical Location</h2>
      <p>
        For any location-dependent business — retail, food service, automotive, personal services —
        the lease is a primary deal input, not a detail. Buyers specifically evaluate:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>Remaining term and renewal options</li>
        <li>Whether the lease can be assigned to the buyer without landlord consent (or with reasonable consent)</li>
        <li>Monthly rent as a percentage of revenue (prime cost benchmarks vary by industry)</li>
        <li>Whether the location can support the business's growth plans</li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        A business with a 5+ year remaining lease, favorable renewal options, and a cooperative landlord
        is materially more attractive than an identical business with a lease expiring in 8 months.
        Secure your lease before going to market.
      </p>

      <h2>6. Growth Trend and Market Position</h2>
      <p>
        Buyers are paying for the future, not the past. A business with consistent 15% annual revenue
        growth commands a higher multiple than a business with flat or declining revenue — even if the
        current SDE is identical. The <a href="/">calculator</a> applies +0.15× for 10–20% growth and
        +0.30× for 20%+ growth, which equals $45,000–$90,000 on a $300,000 SDE business at a 3.0× median.
      </p>
      <p>
        When presenting revenue trends, provide context for any decline. Buyers can accept a down year
        with a clear explanation (COVID impact, one-time project completion, a specific market disruption)
        much better than they accept an unexplained decline. "Revenue dropped 20% in 2023 because a major
        construction client completed their project — new client relationships since then show revenue
        recovering" is a manageable explanation. "Revenue has been declining for three years" without
        explanation is a deal risk.
      </p>

      <h2>7. The Price-to-SDE Multiple Test</h2>
      <p>
        Every sophisticated buyer calculates the implied SDE multiple of your asking price before
        making an offer. They then compare that multiple to:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>The industry median multiple from transaction data (available by industry in the <a href="/">calculator</a>)</li>
        <li>The adjustment factors your business demonstrates (owner involvement, customer concentration, growth trend)</li>
        <li>The financing math: can the business cash-flow the debt service on a typical SBA loan at the asking price?</li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        A business priced at a premium to the industry median multiple needs premium-quality signals to
        justify it. A business priced at or below the industry median is immediately attractive to buyers
        who know the market. Understanding the implied multiple of your asking price — before you set it —
        is essential to pricing your business to sell rather than pricing it to sit.
      </p>
      <p>
        Use the <a href="/">free valuation calculator</a> to understand the range your business supports
        given its current conditions. Then work with a broker to translate that range into an asking
        price strategy. See <a href="/guides/working-with-business-broker/">Working With a Business Broker</a>
        for guidance on broker selection and deal structuring.
      </p>

